description.plain:
Jacques Bermon Webster II (born April 30, 1991), popularly known as Travis Scott (previously stylized as Travi$ Scott) is a rapper and producer from Missouri City, Texas, located within the Houston Metropolitan area. Scott began producing and releasing beats via Myspace at 16.

He moved to Los Angeles after dropping out of The University of Texas at San Antonio following his sophomore year, adopting the name Travi$ Scott in homage to his uncle named Travis, and his musical idol Kid Cudi (real name Scott Mescudi).

Travis Scott dropped out of the University of Texas at San Antonio without his parents knowing and moved to Los Angeles to make music. His parents made a surprise visit to see their son at his former university. They eventually found out that he lied to them. They cut off support towards him from that time on. He ended up sleeping on couches and lived miles away from people he knew.

With some help of fellow southern rapper T.I., Scott signed to Epic Records and T.I.’s label, Grand Hustle. After, he acquired the number of Kanye West’s engineer, Anthony Kilhoffer. With Anthony’s help, Scott was able to co-produce tracks on G.O.O.D. Music’s debut album Cruel Summer. After his appearance on the label’s album, Travis signed to G.O.O.D. Music under a producer contract and along with West’s help, he released his debut solo mixtape Owl Pharaoh.

He released Days Before Rodeo on August 18, 2014, anticipating the release of his debut album entitled Rodeo, which was released September 4th, 2015.

Scott released his highly anticipated sophomore album Birds in the Trap Sing McKnight on September 2, 2016, after previewing it the same morning on the .WAV Radio show on Apple’s Beats 1 platform. The album was an Apple Exclusive and was available exclusively on Apple Music for a week before its full rollout on all other marketplaces and streaming services.

Travis' third studio album ASTROWORLD was released on August 3rd, 2018. The album was a critical and commercial success, selling half a million copies in its first week, and peaking at #1 on the US Billboard 200 chart.

La Flame is also the CEO of Cactus Jack Records, a record label that counts Sheck Wes, Don Toliver, SoFaygo, Luxury Tax 50 and Chase B on its roster.

On July 28, 2023, Travis' highly anticipated fourth full-length studio album, UTOPIA was released after an almost five-year wait from ASTROWORLD. The album was released alongside the Bad Bunny and The Weeknd-accompanied hit single, “K-POP.” The album shares several similarities to Kanye West’s — a producer on the album — June 2013, Yeezus which Travis acted as producer on.

description.plain:
“SICKO MODE” refers to Travis and Drake’s work ethic, showing they’re a cut above the competition by going into “sicko” or “beast” mode.

“Sicko,” or “6icko” (the 6 referring to Drake’s hometown Toronto), is a term derived from Drake’s vernacular. It refers to his friends, brought to the limelight by Golden State Warriors All-Star Kevin Durant, when he tweeted his reaction to Drake’s 2015 diss track, “Charged Up.”

https://twitter.com/KDTrey5/status/625095671595401217?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E625095671595401217&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fgenius.com%2FDrake-summer-sixteen-lyrics

The track has been teased as far back as 2017, when Drake teamed up with Louis Vuitton to release his track “Signs,” and Travis Scott replied to an Instagram post, saying:

Dawg prolly do it for a Louis belt.

songs.full_title: ​goosebumps by Travis Scott (Ft. Kendrick Lamar)
songs.title: ​goosebumps

description.plain:
“goosebumps” is an eerie love song. Travis and Kendrick detail the unique feelings they have for their love interests—especially when she’s not actually there.

Before performing this song live, Travis says he “wrote this song in my bedroom at one of the darkest times in my life.” This, combined with the lyrics in the chorus—specifically such terms as “goosebumps,” “numb,” and “Heimlich”—have led many fans to believe this song may have an underlying theme of prescription drug withdrawal.

The track’s music video was debuted exclusively on Apple Music before being released worldwide on April 3, 2017.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Dst9gZkq1a8

In addition, Travis broke JAY-Z and Kanye West’s record of performing a song the most number of times in a live show (“Niggas in Paris” in France 2012) when he performed “goosebumps” 14 times in a row. Incredibly, he proceeded to break his own record the following week.

songs.full_title: BUTTERFLY EFFECT by Travis Scott
songs.title: BUTTERFLY EFFECT

description.plain:
“BUTTERFLY EFFECT” is Travis Scott’s first solo release of 2017. It serves as the lead single to his third studio album, ASTROWORLD, which was released more than a year after this song. It is produced by Murda Beatz, who has worked with Travis a few times before, most notably on the Texan artist’s September 2016 tracks, “sweet sweet” and “outside.”

The “butterfly effect” is a concept that explains and proves how small causes can have large effects. Travis is also using a double-entendre with “butterfly” wherein, as he refers to the doors on his Lamborghini car; he also describes moving to his new life, how great it is, and how he could never go back to the old one.

On May 15, 2017, Travis released the track on SoundCloud, along with two other songs: “A Man” and “Green & Purple.” However, “BUTTERFLY EFFECT” was the only one out of the three songs that was released as a proper single onto streaming services. The official music video was released almost two months after, on July 13, 2017.

songs.full_title: HIGHEST IN THE ROOM by Travis Scott
songs.title: HIGHEST IN THE ROOM

description.plain:
On “HIGHEST IN THE ROOM,” Travis discusses his relationship with his now-wife and mother of his child – Kylie Jenner – and his self-proclaimed title as the most intoxicated person in the place he is in.

This song was first teased by Kylie on April 22, 2019, when it played in an advertisement for her Kybrows cosmetic product. Following this, on May 3, 2019, Travis performed a portion of the song during his headlining set at JMBLYA 2019, and then again a week later, during his set at Rolling Loud Miami.

In late June 2019, Travis performed a large portion of the track, during his Morocco performance and on August 31, 2019, he previewed Lil Baby’s verse during a live show.

On September 30, 2019, Travis revealed the single’s final release date and cover art in an Instagram post. Coincidentally, two days before the scheduled release of “HIGHEST IN THE ROOM” Travis and Kylie reportedly called it quits on their relationship.

The song was officially released on October 4, 2019, along with accompanying visuals. However, the final version did not include the teased Lil Baby feature. It eventually was released on the song’s remix in December of 2019.

The track also became Scott’s second single to top the Billboard Hot 100 chart, and first to debut in the peak position. “HIGHEST IN THE ROOM” was certified 4x Multi-Platinum by RIAA on December 1, 2020.

songs.full_title: Antidote by Travis Scott
songs.title: Antidote

description.plain:
Produced by Eestbound, WondaGurl, and Travis himself, “Antidote” was not initially intended to appear on Rodeo, as confirmed on Travis' SoundCloud on June 23rd:

This is for the real fans; the real ragers! This is some vibes for the summer. This isn’t on Rodeo… it’s coming soon.

Due to the songs popularity however, this song is now the 9th track on the LP.

This song was first heard live at JMBLYA, and dropped officially on the 21st of June.



The song samples “All I Need” by  Lee Fields & The Expressions.

“Antidote” reached gold & platinum on the same day, December 11, 2015. It went 2x platinum almost exactly a year later on December 12, 2016. It went 3x Platinum on April 14, 2017, and most recently it went 4x platinum on January 31, 2019.

songs.full_title: STARGAZING by Travis Scott
songs.title: STARGAZING

description.plain:
“STARGAZING” is a song describing the experience of an unpredictable psychedelic trip. Travis Scott’s delivery switches between his regular cadence and an auto-tuned falsetto.

The song was first previewed on his Snapchat on April 13, 2018, and has since been performed multiple times live.

Travis released ASTROWORLD’s trailer four days before the album’s release, which featured the song playing over cinematic scenes of Travis Scott navigating a post-apocalyptic landscape with outer space elements.

The song title could be a reference to Houston’s iconic ties to astrological exploration, with NASA’s Mission Control Center being located in Travis’s hometown.

This track as well as “SICKO MODE,” can both be found in the NBA 2K19 Soundtrack

songs.title: ​beibs in the trap

description.plain:
Travis Scott enlists up-and-coming Canadian rapper and record producer NAV on “beibs in the trap,” a standout track from Birds in the Trap Sing McKnight. The song is solely produced by NAV and was originally his record, made before his career started.

The title of the song is a misspelled abbreviation of Canadian singer-songwriter Justin Bieber, who NAV uses to describe the white color of cocaine in the song and even name-drops Bieber in the first verse. It could also be a nod to Nicki Minaj’s May 2012 single “Beez in the Trap,” from her chart-topping sophomore studio album, Pink Friday, but it is clearly a huge nod to Travis Scott’s album title.

The official music video for “beibs in the trap” was released on December 28, 2016. Showing both Travis Scott and NAV in a hangar with a person doing “donuts” in a Lamborghini, its release date coincides with NAV’s manager Cash’s 33rd birthday.

The official music video for “beibs in the trap” was released on December 28, 2016. Showing both Travis Scott and NAV in a hangar with a person doing “donuts” in a Lamborghini, its release date coincides with NAV’s manager Cash’s 33rd birthday.

description.plain:
“90210” is the 5th track from Travis Scott’s debut album Rodeo and his self-professed favorite song on the album.

“90210” is the postal code for Beverly Hills. On the track, Travis waxes lyrical about the different people living there, notably a “porn star girl” who prostitutes herself to pay for her lifestyle and Travis' drug use.

About halfway through the song the beat switches up quite a lot. Travis starts rapping about himself in the first person, in contrast to the first part of the song. Part 2 is also notable for sampling Kanye West’s “Family Business”.

Travis described the overall sound behind the song as trying to capture:

the vibe from when I travel from Texas to L.A…this song is kinda like the vibe, it’s not aggressive, but it’s kinda like the drug.

On August 18th, 2016, almost a full year after the release of Rodeo and this song, Travis released the music video.

songs.full_title: YOSEMITE by Travis Scott (Ft. Gunna & NAV)
songs.title: YOSEMITE

description.plain:
On “YOSEMITE,” Travis Scott enlists Gunna and NAV for a slow-moving track.

On the song, Gunna delivers an effortlessly smooth chorus over signature guitar-driven production by his frequent producer, Turbo. Travis matches Gunna’s free-flowing cadence on the verse as the duo create an ode to their extravagant lives full of jewelry, private jets, and designer clothes.

The track’s title is in reference to Yosemite National Park, a scenic nature park located in California’s Sierra Nevada mountain range.

Additionally, this track is seemingly somewhat of a spiritual successor to Gunna’s April 2018 single “Sold Out Dates”. At the beginning of his verse, Travis seems to mimic the flow of Gunna’s verse on “Sold Out Dates,“ and Gunna’s chorus seems to be a homage to his cadence on that song.

Notably, the song gained attention due to NAV’s outro, which was originally mixed much quieter than Travis and Gunna’s vocals. On August 11, 2018, a better mix, with NAV’s vocals turned up, was added to streaming sites, replacing the old version. Many memes and jokes were made based around his vocal mix, with NAV acknowledging the meme in a now-deleted Instagram post.

The song’s accompanying music video, which stars Travis and Gunna, as well as Travis as a child, debuted on November 30, 2018. This video showed the adult Travis and Gunna in a plane that says ASTROWORLD, watching the child Travis exploring a jungle, looking for ASTROWORLD. NAV, however, was not featured in the video.

description.plain:
On “STOP TRYING TO BE GOD,” Travis cautions rappers to not develop a God complex and to remain true to their roots. The song features Kid Cudi’s signature hums, vocals from Philip Bailey and James Blake, and a harmonica performance by Stevie Wonder.

This was the first song to be conceptualized for the album and also the one that took the longest to complete—it was a year in the making and recorded across multiple studio sessions.

Travis teased the collaboration between him and Stevie Wonder on his Instagram and expressed in a 2018 interview with Billboard that one of his goals for the album was to get a feature from Stevie Wonder:

My next album is going to have Stevie [Wonder]. Well, I’m trying. We’re talking.

The music video, which came out on August 7th, 2018, was directed by Dave Meyers and loaded with Biblical imagery, tying in with the song’s underlying concept.

description.plain:
Travis Scott links up with his idol Kid Cudi for a song about late nights and partying. This song is the second time these two have collaborated on Birds in the Trap Sing McKnight.

Travis flips Cudi’s breakout hit “Day N' Night” during his verse. This is actually the second time that Travis refers to this Cudi hit. Back in 2008, on one of his first musical projects, The Graduates EP with Chris Holloway, one of the tracks was called “Day'n'Nite.”

Travis Scott has talked a lot about how Kid Cudi is one of his favorite artists. Travis said that Kid Cudi liking Rodeo meant so much to him. About Cudi’s participation on Birds in the Trap Sing McKnight, he told Rolling Stone:

In my whole career, all I wanted was acceptance from Kid Cudi…I don’t care about nothing else! This dude saved my life. He kept me from doing a lot of fucked up shit to myself, kept me on the right path. That’s why I make music, that’s why I go hard for the fans, that’s why I tell security to move out the way—‘cause this dude gave me the passion, the information, the insight on how to grow up and be who you want to be.
I don’t know if he remembers, but the first time I ever met Cudi was the first time I met Kanye. I’ve never told anyone this, but it was the same day. That was the first time I was around G.O.O.D. Music at all. I was sitting like, 'Man, I’m in the presence of 'Ye and Cudi. This is the art level where I want to be.’

“NO BYSTANDERS” sees Travis Scott collaborating with Juice WRLD and Sheck Wes, who was signed to Travis' label, Cactus Jack three days after the track. This song is featured on Travis' long-awaited third studio album, ASTROWORLD.

Juice claimed he really wanted to collaborate with Travis and that he was still stuck listening to Travis' debut studio album, Rodeo.

However, Sheck handles the chorus of the track. The chorus was the most controversial part of the song because it interpolates the chorus of Three 6 Mafia’s 1995 track, “Tear da Club Up ‘97, where the group raps:

Tear da club up, nigga, tear da club up
Tear da club up, nigga, tear da club up

Travis was eventually legally sued by DJ Paul from Three 6 Mafia for copyright. In September 2019, word spread that the lawsuit was settled by Travis paying the requested $20 million.

Hours before the album’s release, Travis used this song title along with other ASTROWORLD tracks, consisting of “NC-17,” “STARGAZING,” and “STOP TRYING TO BE GOD” to promote the album on his now-expired Instagram story.

songs.title: FE!N

description.plain:
“FE!N” reunites Atlanta rapper Playboi Carti with Travis Scott, following their 2018 single “Love Hurts” from Carti’s debut studio album, Die Lit.

The allegiance of the two introduces a different soundscape from their previously released material, as Travis experiments with higher vocal pitches, whilst Carti does the opposite and adopts a deeper voice — heard on many snippets presumed to be from his third studio album, Music.

A different version of “FE!N” was previewed in UTOPIA’s accompanying film CIRCUS MAXIMUS, which features an alternate vocal take from Carti, as well as a complete verse from Cactus Jack Records-signee Sheck Wes.

Sheck’s verse was cut from the final album, and only his ad-libs ended up releasing with the final version. However, both UTOPIA’s physical edition and a digital release of the album feature the aforementioned version of “FE!N,” alongside various other elements of the album tweaked last-minute.

“FE!N” debuted at the fifth spot on the Billboard Hot 100, becoming Carti’s highest-charting track yet, as well as Travis' fourteenth to reach the top 10.

description.plain:
On the fourth track of Days Before Rodeo, Travi$ shows us his romantic side, which, at the same time, does not divert from his original, druggy style. Through this chilled, laidback beat, he is experiencing the side effects of drugs he tried–presumably for the first time–while falling in love with a girl he has been around.

Days Before Rodeo has not been released to streaming services, and “Drugs You Should Try It” is no exception. Due to sample clearance, it is unclear if the track will ever see an official release.

He also mentioned that the track is based off of one of his favorite songs, which is Justin Bieber’s “All That Matters.”

On the fourth track of Days Before Rodeo, Travi$ shows us his romantic side, which, at the same time, does not divert from his original, druggy style. Through this chilled, laidback beat, he is experiencing the side effects of drugs he tried–presumably for the first time–while falling in love with a girl he has been around.

Days Before Rodeo has not been released to streaming services, and “Drugs You Should Try It” is no exception. Due to sample clearance, it is unclear if the track will ever see an official release.

He also mentioned that the track is based off of one of his favorite songs, which is Justin Bieber’s “All That Matters.”

description.plain:
“Maria I’m Drunk” revolves around the hazy nights in the life of three super-stars. On Part 1 – “Maria” – Travis personifies weed as a girl. Part 2 -“Drunk” – focuses on the love all three artists share for women and booze.

Part 2 originally premiered on the Rodeo Tour, which led to feverish anticipation for its release. A few months after this debut, the song leaked under the title “Drunk.” The leaked version only featured Travis and Young Thug, without the “Maria” intro, leading to much surprise when Justin Bieber’s name appeared on Rodeo’s final tracklist, whose verse replaced the latter half of Travis’s from the leaked version. Many fans were surprised to see Justin Bieber rap a verse, but his performance was met with rave reviews.

However, the song was only accessible to those who paid for the album, and was not available on any streaming services until September 2018 when Travis announced it would appear on steaming services:

https://mobile.twitter.com/trvisXX/status/1038030343813513222

There are several theories which attempt to explain the 3 year publishing embargo, including music industry politics, and record labels seeking to remove all of Justin Bieber’s rap verses.

Another demo of the song later leaked in the second quarter of 2019, featuring the full version of the “Maria” intro and a different extended Travis verse on “Drunk” from the first leak.

songs.full_title: 3500 by Travis Scott (Ft. 2 Chainz & Future)

description.plain:
“3500” is the first single from Rodeo and was premiered at the Hot 97’s Summer Jam on June 7th, 2015. The title refers to a $3,500 fur coat bought by Kim Kardashian for her daughter North West. It may be hard to make out what exactly costs $3500 – the coke? the code(ine)? –, but Travis confirmed it’s indeed the coat on his instagram.

The song was originally slated for inclusion on Kanye West’s So Help Me God in 2014. According to Scott, it had a “completely different sounding beat,” but the same hook, and was to be a single for West. After West scrapped his vision for SHMG, he gave the track to Scott.

The artwork for the single was shot by Australian director and photographer Nabil Elderkin.

songs.full_title: MELTDOWN by Travis Scott (Ft. Drake)
songs.title: MELTDOWN

description.plain:
“MELTDOWN,” a three-part track that sees the tempo of the track rising until it reaches its untimely climax and the end of part one, sees Travis Scott recruit Drake as they both rap about their superiority in the music industry while the artists give themselves a God-complex, fitting with the theme of the album which is against the Devil.

In the first part of the track, Drake takes control as he raps with a cold and raspy cadence, sending subliminal shots to several artists such as Pharrell Williams and Pusha T. However, in the second part, Travis keeps a similar beat and cadence which is later switched in the third part as his rhythm is slowed down.

Drake’s appearance on the album was teased by fans on Twitter who were given the chance by Travis to listen to the album prior to its release.
